<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">41447923</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>11</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-4529</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>109</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of clinical anesthesia</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Clin Anesth</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Comparison between infraspinatus-Teres minor (ITM) Interfascial block and superior trunk block in shoulder arthroscopy: A randomized non-inferiority trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>112106</StartPage><MedlinePgn>112106</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.jclinane.2025.112106</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0952-8180(25)00367-8</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="STUDY OBJECTIVE">To evaluate whether there are differences in postoperative pain scores and the incidence of hemidiaphragmatic paralysis (HDP) between ultrasound-guided superior trunk block (STB) and infraspinatus teres minor fascial plane block (ITM).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN">Prospective, randomized controlled non-inferiority trial.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SETTING">A tertiary hospital.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PATIENTS">A total of 100 patients aged 18 to 65&#xa0;years scheduled for elective arthroscopic surgery were enrolled.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="INTERVENTIONS">Following sterile skin preparation, patients in the STB group received 15&#xa0;mL of 0.375&#xa0;% ropivacaine, while those in the ITM group received 25&#xa0;mL of 0.375&#xa0;% ropivacaine.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MEASUREMENTS">The primary outcome was the highest resting pain score during the first 24&#xa0;h postoperatively. Secondary outcomes included resting pain scores at six predefined time points (1, 3, 6, 9, 12,and 24&#xa0;h), the incidence and severity of hemidiaphragmatic paralysis (HDP), block performance time, sensory block onset time, duration of analgesia, postoperative rescue analgesic consumption, grip strength, patient satisfaction scores, 24-h Quality of Recovery-15 (QoR-15) assessments, and Overall Benefit of Analgesia Scores (OBAS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MAIN RESULTS">Within 24&#xa0;h postoperation, the highest pain score was 3 [2.0-4.0] in the STB group and 3 [2.8 to 4.3] in the ITM group, with a median difference of 0 (95&#xa0;% CI, -1 to 0). The upper limit of the 95&#xa0;% CI was below the prespecified non-inferiority margin of 1&#x2033;. (non-inferiority P&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.01).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS">For maximal postoperative pain control within 24&#xa0;h after shoulder arthroscopy, the ITM block was noninferior to STB, with significantly reduced diaphragmatic paralysis rates.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025. Published by Elsevier Inc.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>He</LastName><ForeName>Yu</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Anesthesiology, Xuzhou Medical University, Xuzhou, Jiangsu, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhao</LastName><ForeName>Wei</ForeName><Initials>W</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Anesthesiology, The Affiliated Hospital of Xuzhou Medical University, Xuzhou, Jiangsu, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ze</LastName><ForeName>Zhenyu</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Anesthesiology, Xuzhou Medical University, Xuzhou, Jiangsu, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhao</LastName><ForeName>Yan</ForeName><Ini